mes © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Possibly an Americanized form of German   Kriel   or <b>Krüll</b>, a variant of   Kroll   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Kriel","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place called Kriele, near Rathenow (Brandenburg). This surname is rare in Germany.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Croyle  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":4,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":13,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":24,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":26,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":40,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":42,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":55,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John Creel II was born in 1545, in Saffron Walden, Essex, England, his father, John Creel I, was 22 and his mother, Martha, was 15. He married Mary Elizabeth Whitescarver in 1574, in Saffron Walden, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1600, in his hometown, at the age of 55, and was buried in Wiltshire, England."},"et":{"1545–1600":"1545–1600","1555–1628":"1555–1628","1575–1628":"1575–1628","1523–1585":"1523–1585","1530–1604":"1530–1604","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","1544":"1544","1555":"1555","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1574":"1574